<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="523" pageId="1" pageNumber="522" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1908,2043]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1437,151,285]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="523" pageId="1" pageNumber="522">
This group is characterized by the presence of hooked hairs on the mouthparts of the females (
<figureCitation box="[1196,1330,1908,1934]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="13.[151,250,950,974]" captionTargetBox="[194,1393,606,926]" captionTargetId="figure-166@13.[194,1393,606,926]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 9. A–B, mouthparts of A. bonariensis. A, hooked setae on labial palpus. B, hooked setae on prementum and stipes. C, metasomal sterna S1–S4 of A. bonariensis showing modified setae. Scale lines = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4897158" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4897158/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="522">Figs. 9A–B</figureCitation>
). Hooked hairs are present on the stipes, on the prementum and on the first two segments of the labial palpus, except in 
<taxonomicName authority="Holmberg, 1903" authorityName="Holmberg" authorityYear="1903" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Leptergatis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="522" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="halictoides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="522">A. halictoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which lacks such hairs on the second segment of the palpus. One species, 
<taxonomicName authority="Holmberg, 1903" authorityName="Holmberg" authorityYear="1903" box="[1067,1228,1980,2006]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Leptergatis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="522" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bonariensis">
<emphasis box="[1067,1228,1980,2006]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="522">A. bonariensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, also has modified hairs on the hypostomal area of the head, on the trochanters, and on the metasomal sterna (
<figureCitation box="[1170,1258,2016,2042]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="13.[151,250,950,974]" captionTargetBox="[194,1393,606,926]" captionTargetId="figure-166@13.[194,1393,606,926]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 9. A–B, mouthparts of A. bonariensis. A, hooked setae on labial palpus. B, hooked setae on prementum and stipes. C, metasomal sterna S1–S4 of A. bonariensis showing modified setae. Scale lines = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4897158" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4897158/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="522">Fig. 9C</figureCitation>
). Species of the group are 6.2–11.0 mm long. Males have a ventral tubercle in front of the middle coxa, except 
<taxonomicName authority="Holmberg, 1903" authorityName="Holmberg" authorityYear="1903" box="[1200,1362,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Leptergatis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="523" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bonariensis">
<emphasis box="[1200,1362,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="523">A. bonariensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which lacks the tubercles. Yellowish hairs are usually present on the metasomal apical bands and/or on the tibial scopa of females (
<figureCitation box="[255,322,223,249]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1197,1221]" captionTargetBox="[160,1434,182,1173]" captionTargetId="figure-17@5.[154,1434,181,1173]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 1. Females, A. ursinus species group, lateral view. A, A. bonariensis Brèthes. B, A. halictoides (Holmberg). C, A. holmbergi sp. n. D, A. mesopotamica (Holmberg). Scale lines = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4897132" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4897132/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="523">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
), and males of some species are entirely covered by golden pile (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="523">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Haliday" authorityYear="1836" box="[1073,1191,223,249]" class="Liliopsida" family="Pontederiaceae" genus="Ancylosceles" kingdom="Plantae" order="Commelinales" pageId="2" pageNumber="523" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ursinus">A. ursinus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Holmberg" baseAuthorityYear="1903" box="[1203,1400,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Ancyloscelis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="523" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mesopotamica">A. mesopotamica</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Ancyloscelis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="523" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="duckei">A. duckei</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schaller &amp; Roig-Alsina" authorityYear="2021" box="[286,431,259,285]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Ancyloscelis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="523" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="holmbergi">
<emphasis box="[286,431,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="523">A. holmbergi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), or nearly so (
<taxonomicName authority="Holmberg, 1903" authorityName="Holmberg" authorityYear="1903" box="[603,765,259,285]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Leptergatis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="523" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bonariensis">
<emphasis box="[603,765,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="523">A. bonariensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) (
<figureCitation box="[789,858,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1197,1221]" captionTargetBox="[154,1434,181,1173]" captionTargetId="figure-30@6.[154,1434,181,1173]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 2. Males, A. ursinus species group, lateral view. A, A. bonariensis Brèthes. B, A. halictoides (Holmberg). C, A. holmbergi sp. n. D, A. mesopotamica (Holmberg). Scale line= A, C and D, 0.1 mm; B, 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4897134" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4897134/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="523">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
